Wednesday, August 12, 2020

In short, I think itâs become entirely too easy for people using certain programming languages to use libraries from the wide world of clowns that is the Internet. Their ecosystems make it very very easy to become reliant on this stuff. Trouble is, those libraries are frequently ð©. If something about it is broken, you might not be able to code around it, and may have to actually deal with them to get it fixed.

Repeat 100 times, and now you have a real problem brewing.

I have a simple rule: never use a dependency that you could replace with an afternoon of programming.

No dependency is so self-explanatory that you will be able to get it working with less than a few hours of:

  • Searching online to see what solutions to the problem exist.
  • Reading the docs to make sure it actually works for your problem.
  • Reading the code to make sure itâs not complete ð©.
  • Actually wiring it up in your dependency system.
  • Figuring how to tell the dependency to solve your problem.

If you spent that same amount of time writing your own tool:

  • Youâll know exactly how it works and what its shortcomings are.
  • Youâll have something that solves exactly your problem instead of a general problems, so it is certainly shorter and often faster.

Many times, the best approach is first searching online and reading the code to a few other solutions, then writing your own with the knowledge youâve gained from seeing how they work.

There is an argument that dependencies solve bugs so you donât have to. This can be true, but itâs also true that a general solution will have many bugs that you donât care about in your specific solution because it is much harder to write a general program than a specific one.

The long and the short of it is that any code that can be written in less than an afternoon should be handled yourself.

And donât forget about this:

Thereâs a predictable cycle in software ecosystems. Unix, Perl, Windows, Python, PHP/Wordpressâ¦ All have followed a pattern where first the standard library is great, then user libraries take off, then thereâs DLL hell, finally itâs overrun by low quality user-made libraries.

Samâ¢2 years ago

Unfortunately, most programmers can't estimate how long something will take to within half a day. There's lots of projects that I reasonably would have thought I could have built in an afternoon, had I not (by dumb luck) previously had to open up to fix a bug.

General estimates I've seen for programmer productivity are in the 50-100 LOC per day range, which presumably doesn't include bugs found after the fact. Let's be optimistic and say someone can produce 50 lines/day of working, tested code. An afternoon, then, might be 25 LOC. Even the mythical "10x" programmer is only producing a couple hundred lines.

So why would you bother with a dependency manager? That's like complaining about the price of jet fuel, for a trip downstairs to the bodega. You aren't going to spend "a few hours" reading the code and docs. One afternoon's worth of work is a single file which is small enough it'd fit on an Apple IIe screen, without scrolling. Just copy it into your repo. To find out if it will work for you, just look at it. Or write a tiny test program to call the function. If it isn't exactly what you need, fix it right there.

But remember that even a small size won't always save you: Java's binarySearch() clocked in at only 17 lines of code, and it was broken for over 10 years.

This is a somewhat dangerous rule because "what a programmer thinks they can write (correctly) in an afternoon" becomes less ambitious as their experience grows. If a library is big enough (>1 file, >1 screen of code) that it uses a dependency manager to install, you probably want to use the library.

Jeremyâ¢2 years ago

This is a very naive argument. As already mentioned, LOC is totally meaningless. Additionally, the cost of understanding a dependency is significantly more than how big it is. And you even proved your point wrong by virtue of citing binarySearch: short snippets can be hard to understand.

Beyond that, though, a dependency rarely does one tiny thing. It's usually a library full of useful bits where you may or may not need the whole thing, and it may have dependencies of its own. It's easy to find libraries that don't do a ton but are hundreds or thousands of lines of code because, as the author already stated, the libraries are general-purpose. A customized chunk of that may indeed be a tenth the size because you're only writing for your use-case.

The risks of dependencies are also nontrivial, even for trivial projects. HTML specs change, you learn about needing accessible animations, you discover you need to add concurrency. You make the change and the dependency breaks. It can't handle the "for" attribute on a "label" element (yes, I've run into this exact situation). It isn't threadsafe. It is no longer maintained but the version you have doesn't work with Python 3.

Can I predict what will take an afternoon to write? Surely not with 100% accuracy. Can I predict which dependency will be broken and cost me 40 hours to fix next year? Absolutely not.

Carlâ¢2 years ago

I wrote this on HN, but I'll put it here too because I don't think it's worth doing a follow up post, but I do want it on the record:

A lot of people are objecting, "What if you estimate wrong, and it takes more than an afternoon?" This objection is bad.

It is not possible to add a new dependency in less than afternoon because you need to evaluate alternatives, test it, learn how it works, make sure it's not accidentally GPL, etc. So there are not two methods, the less-than-an-afternoon method and the more-than-an-afternoon method. There are two methods that both take at least one afternoon. If you estimate wrong and you can't write the code in an afternoonâ¦ Then stop working on your handwritten version and find a dependency? But now you know what the dependency is really supposed to do and why it's non-trivial, so you're in an even better position to evaluate which ones are good.
